# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: elisp-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Emacs Lisp code is used to modify, extend and customize Emacs.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Those not wanting to write the code themselves can use the Customize function instead.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] It provides a set of preferences pages allowing the user to set options and preview their effect in the running Emacs session.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] When the user saves their changes, Customize simply writes the necessary Emacs Lisp code to the user's config file, which can be set to a special file that only Customize uses, to avoid the possibility of altering the user's own file.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Besides being a programming language that can be compiled to bytecode and to machine code, Emacs Lisp can also function as an interpreted scripting language, much like the Unix Bourne shell or Perl, by calling Emacs in *batch mode*.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] In this way it may be called from the command line or via an executable file, and its editing functions, such as buffers and movement commands are available to the program just as in the normal mode.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] No user interface is presented when Emacs is started in batch mode; it simply executes the passed-in script and exits, displaying any output from the script.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Emacs Lisp is also termed **Elisp**, although there are also older, unrelated Lisp dialects with that name.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Emacs Lisp is most closely related to Maclisp, with some later influence from Common Lisp.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] It supports imperative and functional programming methods.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Lisp was the default extension language for Emacs derivatives such as EINE and ZWEI.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] When Richard Stallman forked Gosling Emacs into GNU Emacs, he also chose Lisp as the extension language, because of its powerful features, including the ability to treat functions as data.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] The Lisp dialect used in Emacs differs substantially from the more modern Common Lisp and Scheme dialects used for applications programming.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] A prominent characteristic of Emacs Lisp is in its use of dynamic rather than lexical scope by default.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] That is, a function may reference local variables in the scope it is called from, but not in the scope where it was defined.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Recently, there has been an ongoing effort to update code to use lexical scoping, for reasons outlined below.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] The development of Emacs Lisp was guided by the goal of providing data structures and features specific to making a versatile text editor over implementing a general-purpose programming language.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] For example, Emacs Lisp cannot easily read a file a line at a time—the entire file must be read into an Emacs buffer.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] However, Emacs Lisp provides many features for navigating and modifying buffer text at a sentence, paragraph, or higher syntactic level as defined by modes.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Here follows a simple example of an Emacs extension written in Emacs Lisp.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] In Emacs, the editing area can be split into separate areas called *windows*, each displaying a different *buffer*.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] A buffer is a region of text loaded into Emacs' memory (possibly from a file) which can be saved into a text document.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Users can press the default C-x 2 key binding to open a new window.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] This runs the Emacs Lisp function `split-window-below`.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Normally, when the new window appears, it displays the same buffer as the previous one.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Suppose we wish to make it display the next available buffer.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] The first statement, `(defun ...)`, defines a new function, `my-split-window-func`, which calls `split-window-below` (the old window-splitting function), then tells the new window to display another (new) buffer.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] The second statement, `(global-set-key ...)` re-binds the key sequence "C-x 2" to the new function.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] This can also be written using the feature named *advice*, which allows a user to create wrappers around extant functions instead of defining their own.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] This has the advantages of not needing keybindings to be changed, of working wherever the original function is called, and of being simpler to write, but the disadvantage of making debugging more complex.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] This instructs `split-window-below` to execute the user-supplied code whenever it is called, after executing the rest of the function.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Advice can also be specified to execute before the original function, around it (literally wrapping the original), or to conditionally execute the original function based on the results of the advice.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Emacs 24.4 replaces this `defadvice` mechanism with `advice-add`, which is claimed to be more flexible and simpler.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] These changes take effect as soon as the code is evaluated.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] It is not necessary to recompile, restart Emacs, or even rehash a configuration file.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] If the code is saved into an Emacs init file, then Emacs will load the extension the next time it starts.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Otherwise, the changes must be reevaluated manually when Emacs is restarted.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Emacs Lisp source code is stored in filesystems as plain text files, by convention with the filename suffix "`.el`".
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] The user's init file is an exception, often appearing as "`.emacs`" despite being evaluated as any Emacs Lisp code.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Since the mid-1990s, Emacs also loads `~/.emacs.el` and `~/.emacs.d/init.el`.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Further, users may specify any file to load as a config file on the command line, or explicitly state that no config file is to be loaded.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] When the files are loaded, an interpreter component of the Emacs program reads and parses the functions and variables, storing them in memory.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] They are then available to other editing functions, and to user commands.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Functions and variables can be freely modified and redefined without restarting the editor or reloading the config file.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] In order to save time and memory space, much of the functionality of Emacs loads only when required.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Each set of optional features shipped with Emacs is implemented by a collection of Emacs code called a package or library.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] For example, there is a library for highlighting keywords in program source code, and a library for playing the game of Tetris.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Each library is implemented using one or more Emacs Lisp source files.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Libraries can define one or more *major modes* to activate and control their function.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Emacs developers write certain functions in C.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] These are *primitives*, also termed *built-in functions* or *subrs*.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Although primitives can be called from Lisp code, they can only be modified by editing the C source files and recompiling.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] In GNU Emacs, primitives are not available as external libraries; they are part of the Emacs executable.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] In XEmacs, runtime loading of such primitives is possible, using the operating system's support for dynamic linking.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Functions may be written as primitives because they need access to external data and libraries not otherwise available from Emacs Lisp, or because they are called often enough that the comparative speed of C versus Emacs Lisp makes a worthwhile difference.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Bytecode still runs more slowly than primitives, but functions loaded as bytecode can be easily modified and re-loaded, and bytecode files are cross-platform software.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] The standard Emacs Lisp code distributed with Emacs is loaded as bytecode, although the matching source files are usually provided for the user's reference as well.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] User-supplied extensions are typically not byte-compiled, as they are neither as large nor as computationally intensive.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] The "cl-lib" package implements a fairly large subset of Common Lisp.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] This package replaces an earlier "cl" package, which would overwrite existing Emacs Lisp function definitions with ones more similar to those found in Common Lisp.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Emacs Lisp (unlike some other Lisp implementations) does not do tail-call optimization.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Without this, tail recursions can eventually lead to stack overflow.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] The apel library aids in writing portable Emacs Lisp code, with the help of the polysylabi platform bridge.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Emacs Lisp is a Lisp-2 like Common Lisp, meaning that it has a function namespace which is separate from the namespace it uses for other variables.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Like MacLisp, Emacs Lisp uses dynamic scope, offering static (or lexical) as an option starting from version 24.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] It can be activated by setting the file local variable `lexical-binding`.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Before this option was added, one could use the `lexical-let` macro from the (now deprecated) "cl" package to provide effective lexical scope.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] In dynamic scoping, if a programmer declares a variable within the scope of a function, it is available to subroutines called from within that function.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Originally, this was intended as an optimization; lexical scoping was still uncommon and of uncertain performance.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] In computer scientist Olin Shivers's recollection, "I asked RMS when he was implementing emacs lisp why it was dynamically scoped and his exact reply was that lexical scope was too inefficient." Dynamic scoping was also meant to provide greater flexibility for user customizations.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] However, dynamic scoping has several disadvantages.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Firstly, it can easily lead to bugs in large programs, due to unintended interactions between variables in different functions.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs-lisp] Secondly, accessing variables under dynamic scoping is generally slower than under lexical scoping.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Emacs has over 10,000 built-in commands and its user interface allows the user to combine these commands into macros to automate work.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Implementations of Emacs typically feature a dialect of the Lisp programming language, allowing users and developers to write new commands and applications for the editor.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Extensions have been written to, among other things, manage files, remote access, e-mail, outlines, multimedia, Git integration, RSS feeds, and collaborative editing, as well as implementations of *ELIZA*, *Pong*, *Conway's Life*, *Snake*, *Dunnet*, and *Tetris*.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The original EMACS was written in 1976 by David A.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Steele Jr. as a set of macros for the TECO editor.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] It was inspired by the ideas of the TECO-macro editors TECMAC and TMACS.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The most popular, and most ported, version of Emacs is GNU Emacs, which was created by Richard Stallman for the GNU Project.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] XEmacs is a variant that branched from GNU Emacs in 1991.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] GNU Emacs and XEmacs use similar Lisp dialects and are, for the most part, compatible with each other.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] XEmacs development is currently very slow.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] GNU Emacs is, along with vi, one of the two main contenders in the traditional editor wars of Unix culture.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] GNU Emacs is among the oldest free and open source projects still under development.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Emacs development began during the 1970s at the MIT AI Lab, whose PDP-6 and PDP-10 computers used the Incompatible Timesharing System (ITS) operating system that featured a default line editor known as Text Editor and Corrector (TECO).
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Unlike most modern text editors, TECO used separate modes in which the user would either add text, edit existing text, or display the document.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] (A similar technique was used to allow overtyping.) This behavior is similar to that of the program ed.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] By the 1970s, TECO was already an old program, initially released in 1962.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Richard Stallman visited the Stanford AI Lab in 1976 and saw the lab's *E* editor, written by Fred Wright.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] He was impressed by the editor's intuitive WYSIWYG (What You See Is What You Get) behavior, which has since become the default behavior of most modern text editors.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] He returned to MIT where Carl Mikkelsen, a hacker at the AI Lab, had added to TECO a combined display/editing mode called *Control-R* that allowed the screen display to be updated each time the user entered a keystroke.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Stallman reimplemented this mode to run efficiently and then added a macro feature to the TECO display-editing mode that allowed the user to redefine any keystroke to run a TECO program.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] E had another feature that TECO lacked: random-access editing.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] TECO was a page-sequential editor that was designed for editing paper tape on the PDP-1 at a time when computer memory was generally small due to cost, and it was a feature of TECO that allowed editing on only one page at a time sequentially in the order of the pages in the file.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Instead of adopting E's approach of structuring the file for page-random access on disk, Stallman modified TECO to handle large buffers more efficiently and changed its file-management method to read, edit, and write the entire file as a single buffer.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Almost all modern editors use this approach.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The new version of TECO quickly became popular at the AI Lab and soon accumulated a large collection of custom macros whose names often ended in *MAC* or *MACS*, which stood for *macro*.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Two years later, Guy Steele took on the project of unifying the diverse macros into a single set.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Steele and Stallman's finished implementation included facilities for extending and documenting the new macro set.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The resulting system was called EMACS, which stood for *Editing MACroS* or, alternatively, *E with MACroS*.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Later, the use of EMACS as a recursive acronym for *EMACS Makes All Computing Simple* became popular; this fit in with the growing use of recursive acronyms for other versions of EMACS.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] (See below.) Stallman picked the name Emacs "because <E> was not in use as an abbreviation on ITS at the time." An apocryphal hacker koan alleges that the program was named after Emack & Bolio's, a popular Boston ice cream store.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The first operational EMACS system existed in late 1976.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Stallman saw a problem in too much customization and *de facto* forking and set certain conditions for usage.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The original Emacs ran only on the PDP-10 running ITS.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Its behavior was sufficiently different from that of TECO that it could be considered a text editor in its own right, and it quickly became the standard editing program on ITS.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Mike McMahon ported Emacs from ITS to the TENEX and TOPS-20 operating systems.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Other contributors to early versions of Emacs include Kent Pitman, Earl Killian, and Eugene Ciccarelli.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] By 1979, Emacs was the main editor used in MIT's AI lab and its Laboratory for Computer Science.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] In the following years, programmers wrote a variety of Emacs-like editors for other computer systems.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] These included EINE (*EINE Is Not EMACS*) and ZWEI (*ZWEI Was EINE Initially*), which were written for the Lisp machine by Mike McMahon and Daniel Weinreb, and Sine (*Sine Is Not Eine*), which was written by Owen Theodore Anderson.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Weinreb's EINE was the first Emacs written in Lisp.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] In 1978, Bernard Greenberg wrote Multics Emacs almost entirely in Multics Lisp at Honeywell's Cambridge Information Systems Lab.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Multics Emacs was later maintained by Richard Soley, who went on to develop the NILE Emacs-like editor for the NIL Project, and by Barry Margolin.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Many versions of Emacs, including GNU Emacs, would later adopt Lisp as an extension language.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] James Gosling, who would later invent NeWS and the Java programming language, wrote Gosling Emacs in 1981.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The first Emacs-like editor to run on Unix, Gosling Emacs was written in C and used Mocklisp, a language with Lisp-like syntax, as an extension language.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Early ads for Computer Corporation of America's *CCA EMACS* (Steve Zimmerman) appeared in 1984.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] CCA EMACS was originally based on Warren Montgomery's EMACS, but was gradually rewritten so that by the time of its commercial release in 1983, none of Montgomery's code was present anymore.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] CCA EMACS was written to emulate the original PDP-10 EMACS (written by Richard Stallman) as closely as possible, while adding many new commands as well.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] In 1984, in a competition with other versions of Emacs, it won a site license from MIT for their Project Athena.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Richard Stallman began work on GNU Emacs in 1984 to produce a free software alternative to the proprietary Gosling Emacs.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] GNU Emacs was initially based on Gosling Emacs, but Stallman's replacement of its Mocklisp interpreter with a true Lisp interpreter required that nearly all of its code be rewritten.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] This became the first program released by the nascent GNU Project.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] GNU Emacs is written in C and provides Emacs Lisp, also implemented in C, as an extension language.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Version 13, the first public release, was made on March 20, 1985.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The first widely distributed version of GNU Emacs was version 15.34, released later in 1985.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Early versions of GNU Emacs were numbered as *1.x.x*, with the initial digit denoting the version of the C core.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The *1* was dropped after version 1.12, as it was thought that the major number would never change, and thus the numbering skipped from *1* to *13*.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] In September 2014, it was announced on the GNU emacs-devel mailing list that GNU Emacs would adopt a rapid release strategy and version numbers would increment more quickly in the future.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] GNU Emacs offered more features than Gosling Emacs, in particular a full-featured Lisp as its extension language, and soon replaced Gosling Emacs as the *de facto* Unix Emacs editor.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Markus Hess exploited a security flaw in GNU Emacs' email subsystem in his 1986 cracking spree in which he gained superuser access to Unix computers.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Most of GNU Emacs functionality is implemented through a scripting language called Emacs Lisp.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Because about 70% of GNU Emacs is written in the Emacs Lisp extension language, one only needs to port the C core which implements the Emacs Lisp interpreter.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] This makes porting Emacs to a new platform considerably less difficult than porting an equivalent project consisting of native code only.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] GNU Emacs development was relatively closed until 1999 and was used as an example of the *Cathedral* development style in *The Cathedral and the Bazaar*.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The project has since adopted a public development mailing list and anonymous CVS access.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Development took place in a single CVS trunk until 2008 and was then switched to the Bazaar DVCS.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] On November 11, 2014, development was moved to Git.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Richard Stallman has remained the principal maintainer of GNU Emacs, but he has stepped back from the role at times.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Stefan Monnier and Chong Yidong were maintainers from 2008 to 2015.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] John Wiegley was named maintainer in 2015 after a meeting with Stallman at MIT.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Wiegley stepped down in 2018, leaving Eli Zaretskii as lead maintainer.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Stefan Kangas was appointed as co-maintainer in 2023, and Andrea Corallo joined Zaretskii and Kangas in 2024.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] As of 2025, GNU Emacs has had 1,608 individual committers throughout its history.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Lucid Emacs, based on an early alpha version of GNU Emacs 19, was developed beginning in 1991 by Jamie Zawinski and others at Lucid Inc.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] One of the best-known early forks in free software development occurred when the codebases of the two Emacs versions diverged and the separate development teams ceased efforts to merge them back into a single program.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Lucid Emacs has since been renamed XEmacs.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Its development is currently very slow, with the most recent stable version 21.4.22 released in January 2009, and the most recent beta released in June 2025; meanwhile, GNU Emacs has implemented many formerly XEmacs-only features.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] In the past, projects aimed at producing small versions of Emacs proliferated.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] GNU Emacs was initially targeted at computers with a 32-bit flat address space and at least 1 MiB of RAM.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Such computers were high end workstations and minicomputers in the 1980s, and this left a need for smaller reimplementations that would run on common personal computer hardware.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Today's computers have more than enough power and capacity to eliminate these restrictions, but small clones have more recently been designed to fit on software installation disks or for use on less capable hardware.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Other projects aim to implement Emacs in a different dialect of Lisp or a different programming language altogether.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Emacs is primarily a text editor and is designed for manipulating pieces of text, although it is capable of formatting and printing documents like a word processor by interfacing with external programs such as LaTeX, Ghostscript or a web browser.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Emacs provides commands to manipulate and differentially display semantic units of text such as words, sentences, paragraphs and source code constructs such as functions.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] It also features *keyboard macros* for performing user-defined batches of editing commands.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] GNU Emacs is a *real-time display* editor, as its edits are displayed onscreen as they occur.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] This is standard behavior for modern text editors but EMACS was among the earliest to implement this.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The alternative is having to issue a distinct command to display text, (e.g. before or after modifying it).
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] This was common in earlier (or merely simpler) line and context editors, such as QED (BTS, CTSS, Multics), ed (Unix), ED (CP/M), and Edlin (DOS).
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Almost all of the functionality in Emacs, including basic editing operations such as the insertion of characters into a file, is achieved through functions written in a dialect of the Lisp programming language.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The dialect used in GNU Emacs is known as Emacs Lisp (Elisp), and was developed expressly to port Emacs to GNU and Unix.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] In this Lisp environment, variables and functions can be modified with no need to rebuild or restart Emacs, with even newly redefined versions of core editor features being asynchronously compiled and loaded into the live environment to replace existing definitions.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Modern GNU Emacs features both bytecode and native code compilation for Emacs Lisp.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] All configuration is stored in variables, classes, and data structures, and changed by simply updating these live.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] In this way there is little difference in practice between customising existing features and writing new ones, both of which are accomplished in the same basic way.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] This is operatively different from most modern extensible editors, for instance VS Code, in which separate languages are used to implement the interface and features of the editor and to encode its user-defined configuration and options.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The main text editing data structure is the *buffer*, a memory region containing data (usually text) with associated attributes.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Any interaction with the editor (like key presses or clicking a mouse button) is realized by evaluating Emacs Lisp code, typically a *command*, which is a function explicitly designed for interactive use.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Keys can be arbitrarily redefined and commands can also be accessed by name; some commands evaluate arbitrary Emacs Lisp code provided by the user in various ways (e.g. a family of `eval-` functions, operating on the `buffer`, `region`, or individual `expression`).
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Even the simplest user inputs (such a printable characters) are effectuated as Emacs Lisp functions, such as the `self-insert-command`, bound by default to most keyboard keys in a typical text editing buffer, mapping the key used to call it into the associated locale-defined character.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] For example, pressing the f key in a buffer that accepts text input evaluates the code `(self-insert-command 1 ?f)`, which inserts one copy of the character constant `?f` *at point*.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The `1`, in this case, is determined by what Emacs terms the *universal argument*: all Emacs command code accepts a numeric value which, in its simplest usage, indicates repetition of an action, but in more complex cases (where repetition doesn't make sense) can yield other behaviours.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] These arguments may be supplied via command prefixes, such as Control+u 7 f, or more compactly Meta+7 f, which expands to `(self-insert-command 7 ?f)`.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] When no prefix is supplied, the universal argument is `1`: every command implicitly runs once, but may be called multiply, or in a different way, when supplied with such a prefix.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Such arguments may also be non-positive where it makes sense for them to be so - it is up to the function accepting the argument to determine, according to its own semantics, what a given number means to it.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] One common usage is for functions to perform actions in reverse simply by checking the sign of the universal argument, such as a sort command which sorts in obverse by default and in reverse when called with a negative argument, using the absolute value of its argument as the sorting key (e.g.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] `-7` sorting in reverse by column index (or delimiter) 7), or undo/redo, which are simply negatives of each other (traversing forward and backward through a recursive history of diffs by some number of steps at a time).
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Because of its relatively large vocabulary of commands, Emacs features a long-established *command language*, to concisely express the keystrokes necessary to perform an action.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] This command language recognises the following shift and modifier keys: Ctrl, Alt, ⇧ Shift, Meta, Super, and Hyper.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Not all of these may be present on an IBM-style keyboard, though they can usually be configured as desired.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] These are represented in command language as the respective prefices: `C-`, `A-`, `S-`, `M-`, `s-`, and `H-`.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Keys whose names are only printable with more than one character are enclosed in angle brackets.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Because Emacs predates modern standard terminology for graphical user interfaces, it uses somewhat divergent names for familiar interface elements.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Depending on configuration, windows can include their own scroll bars, line numbers, sometimes a 'header line' typically to ease navigation, and a *mode line* at the bottom (usually displaying buffer name, the active modes and point position of the buffer among others).
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The bottom of every frame is used for output messages (then called 'echo area') and text input for commands (then called 'minibuffer').
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] In general, Emacs display elements (windows, frames, etc.) do not belong to any specific data or process.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Just as buffers don't require windows, running Emacs processes do not require any frames, and one common usage pattern is to deploy Emacs as an *editing server*: running it as a headless daemon and connecting to it via a frame-spawning client.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] This server can then be made available in any situation where an editor is required, simply by declaring the client program to be the user's `EDITOR` or `VISUAL` variable.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] In this mode of operation, Emacs overlaps the functionality of programs like screen and tmux.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The first Emacs contained a *help* library that included documentation for every command, variable and internal function.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Because of this, Emacs proponents described the software as *self-documenting* in that it presents the user with information on its normal features and its current state.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Each function includes a documentation string that is displayed to the user on request, a practice that subsequently spread to programming languages including Lisp, Java, Perl, and Python.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] This help system can take users to the actual code for each function, whether from a built-in library or an added third-party library.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Emacs displays instructions for performing simple editing commands and invoking the tutorial when it is launched with no file to edit.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The tutorial is by Stuart Cracraft and Richard Stallman.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The *Church of Emacs*, formed by Richard Stallman, is a parody religion created for Emacs users.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] While it refers to vi as the *editor of the beast* (vi-vi-vi being 6-6-6 in Roman numerals), it does not oppose the use of vi; rather, it calls it proprietary software anathema.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] ("Using a free version of vi is not a sin but a penance.") The Church of Emacs has its own newsgroup, alt.religion.emacs, that has posts purporting to support this parody religion.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Supporters of vi have created an opposing *Cult of vi*.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Stallman has jokingly referred to himself as *St I GNU cius*, a saint in the Church of Emacs.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] This is in reference to Ignatius of Antioch, an early Church father venerated in Christianity.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] There is folklore attributing a repetitive strain injury colloquially called *Emacs pinky* to Emacs' strong dependence on modifier keys, although there have not been any studies done to show Emacs causes more such problems than other keyboard-heavy computer programs.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Users have addressed this through various approaches.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] Some users recommend simply using the two Control keys on typical PC keyboards like Shift keys while touch typing to avoid overly straining the left pinky, a proper use of the keyboard will reduce the RSI.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The *Emacs pinky* is a relatively recent development.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The Space-cadet keyboard on which Emacs was developed had oversized Control keys that were adjacent to the space bar and were easy to reach with the thumb.
[src:elisp-deep/emacs] The word *emacs* is sometimes pluralized as *emacsen*, by phonetic analogy with boxen and VAXen, referring to different varieties of Emacs.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] In computing, a **script** is a relatively short and simple set of instructions that typically automate an otherwise manual process.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] The act of writing a script is called **scripting**.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] A **scripting language** or **script language** is a programming language that is used for scripting.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Originally, scripting was limited to automating shells in operating systems, and languages were relatively simple.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Today, scripting is more pervasive and some scripting languages include modern features that allow them to be used to develop application software also.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] A scripting language can be a general-purpose programming language or a domain-specific language for a given environment.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] When embedded in an application, it may be called an *extension language*.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] A scripting language is sometimes referred to as very high-level programming language if it operates at a high level of abstraction, or as a *control language*, especially for job control languages on mainframe computers.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] The term *scripting language* is sometimes used in a wider sense, to refer to dynamic high-level programming languages in general.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Some are strictly interpreted languages, while others use a form of compilation.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] In this context, the term *script* refers to a small program in such a language.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Typically, a script is contained in a single file, and no larger than a few thousand lines of code.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] The scope of scripting languages ranges from small to large, and from highly domain-specific language to general-purpose programming languages.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] A language may start as small and highly domain-specific and later develop into a portable and general-purpose language; conversely, a general-purpose language may later develop special domain-specific dialects.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Script is a subjective characterization that generally includes the following attributes.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] A script is usually not compiled, at least not its usual meaning.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Generally, they are interpreted directly from source code, or from bytecode, or run as native after just-in-time compilation.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] A script is generally relatively short and simple.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] As there is no limit on size or complexity, script is subjective.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] A few lines of code without branching is probably considered a script.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] A codebase of multiple files, that performs sophisticated user or hardware interface or complicated algorithms or multiprogramming is probably not considered a script.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] A script usually automates a task that would otherwise be performed by a person in a more manual way.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] A language that is primarily intended for scripting generally has limited capabilities compared to a general-purpose language.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] A scripting language may lack the functionality to write complex applications.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Typically, a script starts executing at the first line of code whereas an application typically starts at a special point in the code called the entry point.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] For example, Java is not script-like since an application starts at the function named `main` which need not be at the top of the code.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] The following code starts at `main`, then calls `printHelloWorld` which prints "Hello World".
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] In contrast, the following Python code prints "Hello World" without the `main` function or other syntax such as a class definition required by Java.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Scripts are often created or modified by the person executing them, but they are also often distributed, such as when large portions of games are written in a scripting language, notably the Google Chrome T-rex game.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Early mainframe computers (in the 1950s) were non-interactive, instead using batch processing.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] IBM's Job Control Language (JCL) is the archetype of languages used to control batch processing.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] The first interactive shells were developed in the 1960s to enable remote operation of the first time-sharing systems, and these used shell scripts, which controlled running computer programs within a computer program, the shell.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Calvin Mooers in his TRAC language is generally credited with inventing *command substitution*, the ability to embed commands in scripts that, when interpreted, insert a character string into the script.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Louis Pouzin wrote an early processor for command scripts called RUNCOM for CTSS around 1964.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Stuart Madnick at MIT wrote a scripting language for IBM's CP/CMS in 1966.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] He originally called this processor COMMAND, later named EXEC.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Multics included an offshoot of CTSS RUNCOM, also called RUNCOM.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] EXEC was eventually replaced by EXEC 2 and Rexx.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Languages such as Tcl and Lua were specifically designed as general-purpose scripting languages that could be embedded in any application.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Other languages such as Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) provided strong integration with the automation facilities of an underlying system.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Embedding of such general-purpose scripting languages instead of developing a new language for each application also had obvious benefits, relieving the application developer of the need to code a language translator from scratch and allowing the user to apply skills learned elsewhere.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Some software incorporates several different scripting languages.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Modern web browsers typically provide a language for writing extensions to the browser itself, and several standard embedded languages for controlling the browser, including JavaScript (a dialect of ECMAScript) or XUL.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Scripting languages can be categorized into several different types, with a considerable degree of overlap among the types.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Scripting is often contrasted with system programming, as in Ousterhout's dichotomy or "programming in the large and programming in the small".
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] In this view, scripting is glue code, connecting software components, and a language specialized for this purpose is a *glue language*.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Pipelines and shell scripting are archetypal examples of glue languages, and Perl was initially developed to fill this same role.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Web development can be considered a use of glue languages, interfacing between a database and web server.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] But if a substantial amount of logic is written in script, it is better characterized as simply another software component, not "glue".
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Macro languages exposed to operating system or application components can serve as glue languages.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] These include Visual Basic for Applications, WordBasic, LotusScript, CorelScript, Hummingbird Basic, QuickScript, Rexx, SaxBasic, and WinWrap Basic.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Other tools like AWK can also be considered glue languages, as can any language implemented by a Windows Script Host engine (VBScript, JScript and VBA by default in Windows and third-party engines including implementations of Rexx, Perl, Tcl, Python, XSLT, Ruby, Modern Pascal, Delphi, and C).
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] A majority of applications can access and use operating system components via the object models or its own functions.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Depending upon the OS version, WSH and the default script engines (VBScript and JScript) are available.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Programmable calculators can be programmed in glue languages in three ways.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] For example, the Texas Instruments TI-92, by factory default can be programmed with a command script language.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Inclusion of the scripting and glue language Lua in the TI-NSpire series of calculators could be seen as a successor to this.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] The primary on-board high-level programming languages of most graphing calculators (most often Basic variants, sometimes Lisp derivatives, and more uncommonly, C derivatives) in many cases can glue together calculator functions—such as graphs, lists, matrices, etc.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Third-party implementations of more comprehensive Basic version that may be closer to variants listed as glue languages in this article are available—and attempts to implement Perl, Rexx, or various operating system shells on the TI and HP graphing calculators are also mentioned.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] A number of text editors support macros written either using a macro language built into the editor, e.g., The SemWare Editor (TSE), vi improved (VIM), or using an external implementation, e.g., XEDIT, or both, e.g., KEDIT.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Sometimes text editors and edit macros are used under the covers to provide other applications, e.g., FILELIST and RDRLIST in CMS .
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Many of these languages' interpreters double as command-line interpreters such as the Unix shell or the MS-DOS `COMMAND.COM`.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Others, such as AppleScript offer the use of English-like commands to build scripts.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] With the advent of graphical user interfaces, a specialized kind of scripting language emerged for controlling a computer.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] These languages interact with the same graphic windows, menus, buttons, and so on, that a human user would.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] They do this by simulating the actions of a user.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] These languages are typically used to automate user actions.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Such languages are also called *macros* when control is through simulated key presses or mouse clicks, and tapping or pressing on a touch-activated screen.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] These languages could in principle be used to control any GUI application, but in practice their use is limited because they need support from the application and from the operating system.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] There are a few exceptions to this limit.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Some GUI scripting languages are based on recognizing graphical objects from their display screen pixels.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] These GUI scripting languages do not depend on support from the operating system or application.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] When the GUI provides the appropriate interfaces, as in the IBM Workplace Shell, a generic scripting language, e.g., Object REXX, can be used to write GUI scripts.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Likewise, many computer game systems use a custom scripting language to express the programmed actions of non-player characters and the game environment.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Languages of this sort are designed for a single application; while they may superficially resemble a specific general-purpose language (e.g., QuakeC, modeled after C), they have custom features that distinguish them.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Emacs Lisp, while a fully formed and capable dialect of Lisp, contains many special features that make it most useful for extending the editing functions of Emacs.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] An application-specific scripting language can be viewed as a domain-specific programming language specialized to one application.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] A number of languages have been designed for the purpose of replacing application-specific scripting languages by being embeddable in application programs.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] The application programmer (working in C or another systems language) includes "hooks" where the scripting language can control the application.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] These languages may be technically equivalent to an application-specific extension language but when an application embeds a "common" language, the user gets the advantage of being able to transfer skills from application to application.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] A more generic alternative is simply to provide a library (often a C library) that a general-purpose language can use to control the application, without modifying the language for the specific domain.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] JavaScript began as, and still is mostly, a language for scripting inside web browsers.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] However, the standardizing of the language as ECMAScript has made it popular as a general-purpose embeddable language.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] The Mozilla implementation SpiderMonkey is embedded in several environments such as the Yahoo Widgets Engine,and applications such as the Adobe products Flash (ActionScript) and Acrobat (for scripting PDF files).
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Tcl was created as an extension language but has come to be used more often as a general-purpose language in roles similar to Python, Perl, and Ruby.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] In contrast, Rexx was created as a job control language, but is widely used as an extension language and a general-purpose language.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Perl is a general-purpose language, but had the Oraperl (1990) dialect, consisting of a Perl 4 binary with Oracle Call Interface compiled in.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] This has however since been replaced by a library (Perl Module), DBD::Oracle.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Other complex and task-oriented applications may incorporate and expose an embedded programming language to allow their users more control and give them more functionality than can be available through a user interface, no matter how sophisticated.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] For example, Autodesk Maya 3D authoring tools embed the Maya Embedded Language, or Blender which uses Python to fill this role.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] Some other types of applications that need faster feature addition or tweak-and-run cycles (e.g. game engines) also use an embedded language.
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] During the development, this allows them to prototype features faster and tweak more freely, without the need for the user to have intimate knowledge of the inner workings of the application or to rebuild it after each tweak (which can take a significant amount of time).
[src:elisp-deep/extension-language] The scripting languages used for this purpose range from the more common and more famous Lua and Python to lesser-known ones such as AngelScript and Squirrel.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The program's tagline is "the extensible self-documenting text editor." Most functionality in GNU Emacs is implemented in user-accessible Emacs Lisp, allowing deep extensibility directly by users and through community-contributed packages.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Its built-in features include a file browser and editor (Dired), an advanced calculator (Calc), an email client and news reader (Gnus), a Language Server Protocol integration, and the productivity system Org-mode.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] A large community of users have contributed extensions such as the Git interface Magit, the Vim emulation layer Evil, several search frameworks, the window manager EXWM, and tools for working with a wide range of programming languages.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Steele Jr. as a set of macros for the TECO editor, and in 1984, Richard Stallman began work on GNU Emacs, to produce a free software replacement to the proprietary Gosling Emacs.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] This became the first program released by the then-nascent GNU Project.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Early versions of GNU Emacs were numbered as "1.x.x," with the initial digit denoting the version of the C core.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The "1" was dropped after version 1.12 as it was thought that the major number would never change, and thus the major version skipped from "1" to "13".
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] A new third version number was added to represent changes made by user sites.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] In the current numbering scheme, a number with two components signifies a release version, with development versions having three components.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs was later ported to the Unix operating system.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] It offered more features than Gosling Emacs, in particular a full-featured Lisp as its extension language, and soon replaced Gosling Emacs as the *de facto* Unix Emacs editor.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Markus Hess exploited a security flaw in GNU Emacs's email subsystem in his 1986 cracking spree, in which he gained superuser access to Unix computers.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Although users commonly submitted patches and Elisp code to the net.emacs newsgroup, participation in GNU Emacs development was relatively restricted until 1999, and was used as an example of the "Cathedral" development style in *The Cathedral and the Bazaar*.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Development took place in a single CVS trunk until 2008, and today uses the Git DVCS.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Stefan Monnier and Chong Yidong oversaw maintenance from 2008.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] On September 21, 2015, Monnier announced that he would be stepping down as maintainer effective with the feature freeze of Emacs 25.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Longtime contributor John Wiegley was announced as the new maintainer on November 5, 2015.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Wiegley was joined by Eli Zaretskii in July, 2016, and Lars Ingebrigtsen in September, 2020.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Wiegley stepped down in 2018, and Ingebrigtsen concluded his term with the release of Emacs 29.1, leaving Zaretskii as lead maintainer.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The terms of the GNU General Public License (GPL) state that the Emacs source code, including both the C and Emacs Lisp components, are freely available for examination, modification, and redistribution.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Older versions of the GNU Emacs documentation appeared under an ad-hoc license that required the inclusion of certain text in any modified copy.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] In the GNU Emacs user's manual, for example, this included instructions for obtaining GNU Emacs and Richard Stallman's essay *The GNU Manifesto*.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The XEmacs manuals, which were inherited from older GNU Emacs manuals when the fork occurred, have the same license.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Newer versions of the documentation use the GNU Free Documentation License with "invariant sections" that require the inclusion of the same documents and that the manuals proclaim themselves as *GNU Manuals*.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] This policy is in place so that the FSF can defend the software in court if its copyleft license is violated.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] In 2011, it was noticed that GNU Emacs had been accidentally releasing some binaries without corresponding source code for two years, in opposition to the intended spirit of the GPL.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Richard Stallman described this incident as "a very bad mistake," which was promptly fixed.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The FSF did not sue any downstream redistributors who unknowingly violated the GPL by distributing these binaries.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] In its normal editing mode, GNU Emacs behaves like common text editors by allowing the user to type text with the keyboard and move the editing point with arrow keys.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Escape key sequences or pressing the control key and/or the meta key, alt key or super keys in conjunction with a regular key produces modified keystrokes that invoke functions from the Emacs Lisp environment.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Commands such as `save-buffer` and `save-buffers-kill-emacs` combine multiple modified keystrokes.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Some GNU Emacs commands work by invoking external programs, such as ispell for spell-checking and the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) for program compilation.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Emacs also supports "inferior processes," long-lived child processes that interact with the editor.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] This is used to implement shell-mode, running a Unix shell as inferior process, as well as read–eval–print loop (REPL) modes for various programming languages.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Emacs' support for external processes makes it suitable for interactive programming along the lines of Interlisp or Smalltalk.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Users who prefer the widely used IBM Common User Access keyboard shortcut layout can use cua-mode, a package that originally was a third-party add-on but has been included in GNU Emacs since version 22.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Emacs uses the "minibuffer," normally the bottommost line, to display messages and request information, functions that are often performed by dialog boxes in GUI editors.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The minibuffer holds information such as text to target in a search or the name of a file to read or save.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] When applicable, command-line completion is available using the tab and space keys.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Emacs keeps text in data structures known as buffers.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Buffers may or may not be displayed onscreen, and all buffer features are accessible by both Emacs Lisp programs and the user interface.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The user can create new buffers and dismiss unwanted ones, and many buffers can exist at the same time, limited only by available memory.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Emacs can be configured to save the list of open buffers on exit, and reopen this list when it is restarted.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Some buffers contain text loaded from text files, which the user can edit and save back to permanent storage.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] These buffers are said to be "visiting" files.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Buffers also serve to display other data, such as the output of Emacs commands, dired directory listings, documentation strings displayed by the "help" library and notification messages that in other editors would be displayed in a dialog box.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Some of these notifications are displayed briefly in the minibuffer, and GNU Emacs provides a *Messages* buffer that keeps a history of the most recent notifications of this type.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] When the minibuffer is used for output from Emacs, it is called the "echo area".
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Longer notifications are displayed in buffers of their own.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The maximum length of messages that will be displayed in the minibuffer is, of course, configurable.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Buffers can also serve as input and output areas for an external process such as a shell or REPL.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Buffers which Emacs creates on its own are typically named with asterisks on each end, to distinguish from user buffers.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The list of open buffers is itself displayed in this type of buffer.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Most Emacs key sequences remain functional in any buffer.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] For example, the standard Ctrl-s `isearch` function can be used to search filenames in dired buffers, and the file list can be saved to a text file just as any other buffer.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Dired buffers can be switched to a writable mode, in which filenames and attributes can be edited textually; when the buffer is saved, the changes are written to the filesystem.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] This allows multiple files to be renamed using the search and replace features of Emacs.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] When so equipped, Emacs displays image files in buffers.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Emacs can split the editing area into separate non-overlapping sections called "windows," a feature that has been available since 1975, predating the graphical user interface in common use.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] In Emacs terminology, "windows" are similar to what other systems call "frames" or "panes" – a rectangular portion of the program's display that can be updated and interacted with independently.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Each Emacs window has a status bar called the "mode line" displayed by default at the bottom edge of the window.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Emacs windows are available both in text-terminal and graphical modes and allow more than one buffer, or several parts of a buffer, to be displayed at once.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] In addition, there is follow-mode, a minor mode that chains windows to display non-overlapping portions of a buffer.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Using follow-mode, a single file can be displayed in multiple side-by-side windows that update appropriately when scrolled.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] In addition, Emacs supports "narrowing" a buffer to display only a portion of a file, with top/bottom of buffer navigation functionality and buffer size calculations reflecting only the selected range.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Emacs windows are tiled and cannot appear "above" or "below" their companions.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Emacs can launch multiple "frames", which are displayed as individual windows in a graphical environment.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] On a text terminal, multiple frames are displayed stacked filling the entire terminal, and can be switched using the standard Emacs commands.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs can display or edit a variety of different types of text and adapts its behavior by entering add-on modes called "major modes".
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] There are major modes for many different purposes including editing ordinary text files, the source code of many markup and programming languages, as well as displaying web pages, directory listings and other system info.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Each major mode involves an Emacs Lisp program that extends the editor to behave more conveniently for the specified type of text.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The use of "minor modes" enables further customization.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] A GNU Emacs editing buffer can use only one major mode at a time, but multiple minor modes can operate simultaneously.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] These may operate directly on documents, as in the way the major mode for the C programming language defines a separate minor mode for each of its popular indent styles, or they may alter the editing environment.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Examples of the latter include a mode that adds the ability to undo changes to the window configuration and one that performs on-the-fly syntax checking.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] There is also a minor mode that allows multiple major modes to be used in a single file, for convenience when editing a document in which multiple programming languages are embedded.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs supports the capability to use it as an interpreter for the Emacs Lisp language without displaying the text editor user interface.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] In batch mode, user configuration is not loaded and the terminal interrupt characters C-c and C-z will have their usual effect of exiting the program or suspending execution instead of invoking Emacs keybindings.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs has command line options to specify either a file to load and execute, or an Emacs Lisp function may be passed in from the command line.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Emacs will start up, execute the passed-in file or function, print the results, then exit.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The shebang line `#!/usr/bin/emacs --script` allows the creation of standalone scripts in Emacs Lisp.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The *GNU Emacs Manual*, written by Richard Stallman, is bundled with GNU Emacs and can be viewed with the built-in info browser.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Two additional manuals, the *Emacs Lisp Reference Manual* by Bil Lewis, Richard Stallman, and Dan Laliberte and *An Introduction to Programming in Emacs Lisp* by Robert Chassell, are included.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] All three manuals are also published in book form by the Free Software Foundation.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs has support for many alphabets, scripts, writing systems, and cultural conventions and provides spell-checking for many languages by calling external programs such as ispell.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Version 24 added support for bidirectional text and left-to-right and right-to-left writing direction for languages such as Arabic, Persian and Hebrew.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Many character encoding systems, including UTF-8, are supported.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs uses UTF-8 for its encoding as of version 23, while prior versions used their own encoding internally and performed conversion upon load and save.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The internal encoding used by XEmacs is similar to that of GNU Emacs but differs in details.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The GNU Emacs user interface originated in English and, with the exception of the beginners' tutorial, has not been translated into any other language.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] A subsystem called *Emacspeak* enables visually impaired and blind users to control the editor through audio feedback.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The behavior of GNU Emacs can be modified and extended almost without limit by incorporating Emacs Lisp programs that define new commands, new buffer modes, new keymaps, add command-line options, and so on.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Many extensions providing user-facing functionality define a major mode (either for a new file type or to build a non-text-editing user interface); others define only commands or minor modes, or provide functions that enhance another extension.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Since version 24 GNU Emacs includes a built-in package manager accessible with the `list-packages` command that allows users to search for and install packages.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Historically, packages were downloaded manually, often distributed through the Usenet newsgroup gnu.emacs.sources.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Now, packages can be retrieved from various ELPA (Emacs Lisp Package Archive) repositories, including one run by the GNU Project.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Over time many popular packages have been included in Emacs by default; for example version 21 began bundling Org-mode, Calc, TRAMP, and many others.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] In its early history, GNU Emacs often ran noticeably slower than rival text editors because the loading and interpreting of its Lisp-based code incurs a performance overhead.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Modern computers are powerful enough to run GNU Emacs with ease, but versions prior to 19.29 (released in 1995) couldn't edit files larger than 8 MB.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The file size limit was raised in successive versions, and 32 bit versions after GNU Emacs 23.2 can edit files up to 512 MB in size.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Emacs compiled on a 64-bit machine can handle much larger buffers.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] While GNU Emacs is largely written in Emacs Lisp, it makes extensive use of natively compiled C code to improve performance.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] In addition to its own C code, it uses external libraries such as libxml2 for parsing XML.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Packages installed by the user can load dynamic modules.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Since version 28.1, Emacs can natively compile Emacs Lisp files via `libgccjit`, as opposed to just byte compiling them, resulting in a significant boost in performance.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs runs on a wide variety of operating systems, including DOS, Windows, and most Unix-like operating systems, such as Linux, the various BSDs, Solaris, AIX, HP-UX and macOS.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Many Unix-like systems include Emacs by default.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] In 2023 an official port for Android was released.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Version 23.1 removed support for some platforms deemed obsolete.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs runs both on text terminals and in graphical user interface (GUI) environments.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] On Unix-like operating systems, GNU Emacs can use the X Window System to produce its GUI either directly using Athena widgets or by using a "widget toolkit" such as Motif, LessTif, or GTK+.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs can also use the graphics systems native to macOS and Windows to provide menubars, toolbars, scrollbars and context menus conforming more closely to each platform's look and feel.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] The correct spelling is "GNU Emacs", not "GNU/Emacs", following the rules of English, in the construction "GNU Emacs" the word "GNU" modifies "Emacs." That is the right way to describe a program called Emacs which is a GNU package.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Lucid Emacs, based on an early version of GNU Emacs 19, was developed beginning in 1991 by Jamie Zawinski and others at Lucid Inc.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] One of the best-known forks in free software development occurred when the codebases of the two Emacs versions diverged and the separate development teams ceased efforts to merge them back into a single program.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] After Lucid filed for bankruptcy, Lucid Emacs was renamed XEmacs.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] XEmacs development has slowed, with the most recent stable version 21.4.22 released in January 2009, while GNU Emacs has implemented many formerly XEmacs-only features.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] This has led some users to proclaim XEmacs' obsolescence.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Changes in each Emacs release are listed in a NEWS file distributed with Emacs.
[src:elisp-deep/gnu-emacs] Changes brought about by *downgrading* to the previous release are listed in an "Antinews" file, often with some snarky commentary on why this might be desirable.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was originally created as a practical mathematical notation for computer programs, influenced by (though not originally derived from) the notation of Alonzo Church's lambda calculus.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] It quickly became a favored programming language for artificial intelligence (AI) research.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] As one of the earliest programming languages, Lisp pioneered many ideas in computer science, including tree data structures, automatic storage management, dynamic typing, conditionals, higher-order functions, recursion, the self-hosting compiler, and the read–eval–print loop.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The name *LISP* derives from "List Processor".
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Linked lists are one of Lisp's major data structures, and Lisp source code is made of lists.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Thus, Lisp programs can manipulate source code as a data structure, giving rise to the macro systems that allow programmers to create new syntax or new domain-specific languages embedded in Lisp.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The interchangeability of code and data gives Lisp its instantly recognizable syntax.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] All program code is written as *s-expressions*, or parenthesized lists.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A function call or syntactic form is written as a list with the function or operator's name first, and the arguments following; for instance, a function `f` that takes three arguments would be called as `(f arg1 arg2 arg3)`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] John McCarthy began developing Lisp in 1958 while he was at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Due to these factors, he consulted on the design of the Fortran List Processing Language, which was implemented as a Fortran library.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] However, he was dissatisfied with it because it did not support recursion or a modern if-then-else statement (which was a new concept when Lisp was first introduced).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy's original notation used bracketed "M-expressions" that would be translated into S-expressions.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] As an example, the M-expression `car[cons[A,B]]` is equivalent to the S-expression `(car (cons A B))`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Once Lisp was implemented, programmers rapidly chose to use S-expressions, and M-expressions were abandoned.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] M-expressions surfaced again with short-lived attempts of MLisp by Horace Enea and CGOL by Vaughan Pratt.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was first implemented by Steve Russell on an IBM 704 computer using punched cards.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Russell was working for McCarthy at the time and realized (to McCarthy's surprise) that the Lisp *eval* function could be implemented in machine code.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The result was a working Lisp interpreter which could be used to run Lisp programs, or more properly, "evaluate Lisp expressions".
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp dialects still use `car` and `cdr` (/kɑːr/ and /ˈkʊdər/) for the operations that return the first item in a list and the rest of the list, respectively.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy published Lisp's design in a paper in *Communications of the ACM* on April 1, 1960, entitled "Recursive Functions of Symbolic Expressions and Their Computation by Machine, Part I".
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] He showed that with a few simple operators and a notation for anonymous functions borrowed from Church, one can build a Turing-complete language for algorithms.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This compiler introduced the Lisp model of incremental compilation, in which compiled and interpreted functions can intermix freely.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The language used in Hart and Levin's memo is much closer to modern Lisp style than McCarthy's earlier code.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Garbage collection routines were developed by MIT graduate student Daniel Edwards, prior to 1962.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] During the 1980s and 1990s, a great effort was made to unify the work on new Lisp dialects (mostly successors to Maclisp such as ZetaLisp and NIL (New Implementation of Lisp)) into a single language.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The new language, Common Lisp, was somewhat compatible with the dialects it replaced (the book *Common Lisp the Language* notes the compatibility of various constructs).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] In 1994, ANSI published the Common Lisp standard, "ANSI X3.226-1994 Information Technology Programming Language Common Lisp".
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Since its inception, Lisp was closely connected with the artificial intelligence research community, especially on PDP-10 systems.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was used as the implementation of the language Micro Planner, which was used in the famous AI system SHRDLU.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] In the 1970s, as AI research spawned commercial offshoots, the performance of existing Lisp systems became a growing issue, as programmers needed to be familiar with the performance ramifications of the various techniques and choices involved in the implementation of Lisp.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Over its sixty-year history, Lisp has spawned many variations on the core theme of an S-expression language.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Some of these variations have been standardized and implemented by different groups with different priorities (for example, both Common Lisp and Scheme have multiple implementations).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] However, in other cases a software project defines a Lisp without a standard and there is no clear distinction between the dialect and the implementation (for example, Clojure and Emacs Lisp fall into this category).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Differences between dialects (and/or implementations) may be quite visible—for instance, Common Lisp uses the keyword `defun` to name a function, but Scheme uses `define`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Within a dialect that is standardized conforming implementations support the same core language, but with different extensions and libraries.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This sometimes also creates quite visible changes from the base language - for instance, Guile (an implementation of Scheme) uses `define*` to create functions which can have default arguments and/or keyword arguments, neither of which are standardized.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] After having declined somewhat in the 1990s, Lisp has experienced a resurgence of interest after 2000.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Most new activity has been focused around implementations of Common Lisp, Scheme, Emacs Lisp, Clojure, and Racket, and includes development of new portable libraries and applications.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Many new Lisp programmers were inspired by writers such as Paul Graham and Eric S.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Raymond to pursue a language others considered antiquated.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] New Lisp programmers often describe the language as an eye-opening experience and claim to be substantially more productive than in other languages.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This increase in awareness may be contrasted to the "AI winter" and Lisp's brief gain in the mid-1990s.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] As of 2010, there were eleven actively maintained Common Lisp implementations.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] *Common-lisp.net* is a hosting site for open source Common Lisp projects.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Quicklisp is a library manager for Common Lisp.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Fifty years of Lisp (1958–2008) was celebrated at LISP50@OOPSLA.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] There are regular local user meetings in Boston, Vancouver, and Hamburg.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Other events include the European Common Lisp Meeting, the European Lisp Symposium and an International Lisp Conference.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The Scheme community actively maintains over twenty implementations.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Several significant new implementations (Chicken, Gambit, Gauche, Ikarus, Larceny, Ypsilon) have been developed in the 2000s (decade).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The Revised5 Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme standard of Scheme was widely accepted in the Scheme community.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The Scheme Requests for Implementation process has created a lot of quasi-standard libraries and extensions for Scheme.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] User communities of individual Scheme implementations continue to grow.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A new language standardization process was started in 2003 and led to the R6RS Scheme standard in 2007.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Academic use of Scheme for teaching computer science seems to have declined somewhat.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Some universities are no longer using Scheme in their computer science introductory courses; MIT now uses Python instead of Scheme for its undergraduate computer science program and MITx massive open online course.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] There are several new dialects of Lisp: Arc, Hy, Nu, Liskell, and LFE (Lisp Flavored Erlang).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The parser for Julia is implemented in Femtolisp, a dialect of Scheme (Julia is inspired by Scheme, which in turn is a Lisp dialect).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp and Scheme represent two major streams of Lisp development.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] These languages embody significantly different design choices.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The primary influences were Lisp Machine Lisp, Maclisp, NIL, S-1 Lisp, Spice Lisp, and Scheme.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] It has many of the features of Lisp Machine Lisp (a large Lisp dialect used to program Lisp Machines), but was designed to be efficiently implementable on any personal computer or workstation.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp is a general-purpose programming language and thus has a large language standard including many built-in data types, functions, macros and other language elements, and an object system (Common Lisp Object System).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp also borrowed certain features from Scheme such as lexical scoping and lexical closures.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp implementations are available for targeting different platforms such as the LLVM, the Java virtual machine, x86-64, PowerPC, Alpha, ARM, Motorola 68000, and MIPS, and operating systems such as Windows, macOS, Linux, Solaris, FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD, Dragonfly BSD, and Heroku.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Scheme is a statically scoped and properly tail-recursive dialect of the Lisp programming language invented by Guy L.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] It was designed to have exceptionally clear and simple semantics and few different ways to form expressions.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Designed about a decade earlier than Common Lisp, Scheme is a more minimalist design.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] It has a much smaller set of standard features but with certain implementation features (such as tail-call optimization and full continuations) not specified in Common Lisp.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A wide variety of programming paradigms, including imperative, functional, and message passing styles, find convenient expression in Scheme.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Scheme continues to evolve with a series of standards (Revisedn Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme) and a series of Scheme Requests for Implementation.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Clojure is a dialect of Lisp that targets mainly the Java virtual machine, and the Common Language Runtime (CLR), the Python VM, the Ruby VM YARV, and compiling to JavaScript.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] It is designed to be a pragmatic general-purpose language.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Clojure draws considerable influences from Haskell and places a very strong emphasis on immutability.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Clojure provides access to Java frameworks and libraries, with optional type hints and type inference, so that calls to Java can avoid reflection and enable fast primitive operations.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Clojure is not designed to be backwards compatible with other Lisp dialects.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Further, Lisp dialects are used as scripting languages in many applications, with the best-known being Emacs Lisp in the Emacs editor, AutoLISP and later Visual Lisp in AutoCAD, Nyquist in Audacity, and Scheme in LilyPond.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The potential small size of a useful Scheme interpreter makes it particularly popular for embedded scripting.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Examples include SIOD and TinyScheme, both of which have been successfully embedded in the GIMP image processor under the generic name "Script-fu".
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] LIBREP, a Lisp interpreter by John Harper originally based on the Emacs Lisp language, has been embedded in the Sawfish window manager.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp has officially standardized dialects: R6RS Scheme, R7RS Scheme, IEEE Scheme, ANSI Common Lisp and ISO ISLISP.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was the first language where the structure of program code is represented faithfully and directly in a standard data structure—a quality much later dubbed "homoiconicity".
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Thus, Lisp functions can be manipulated, altered or even created within a Lisp program without lower-level manipulations.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This is generally considered one of the main advantages of the language with regard to its expressive power, and makes the language suitable for syntactic macros and meta-circular evaluation.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A conditional using an *if–then–else* syntax was invented by McCarthy for a chess program written in Fortran.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] He proposed its inclusion in ALGOL, but it was not made part of the Algol 58 specification.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] For Lisp, McCarthy used the more general *cond*-structure.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Algol 60 took up *if–then–else* and popularized it.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp deeply influenced Alan Kay, the leader of the research team that developed Smalltalk at Xerox PARC; and in turn Lisp was influenced by Smalltalk, with later dialects adopting object-oriented programming features (inheritance classes, encapsulating instances, message passing, etc.) in the 1970s.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The Flavors object system introduced the concept of multiple inheritance and the mixin.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The Common Lisp Object System provides multiple inheritance, multimethods with multiple dispatch, and first-class generic functions, yielding a flexible and powerful form of dynamic dispatch.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Many years later, Alan Kay suggested that as a result of the confluence of these features, only Smalltalk and Lisp could be regarded as properly conceived object-oriented programming systems.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp introduced the concept of automatic garbage collection, in which the system walks the heap looking for unused memory.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Progress in modern sophisticated garbage collection algorithms such as generational garbage collection was stimulated by its use in Lisp.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Largely because of its resource requirements with respect to early computing hardware (including early microprocessors), Lisp did not become as popular outside of the AI community as Fortran and the ALGOL-descended C language.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Because of its suitability to complex and dynamic applications, Lisp enjoyed some resurgence of popular interest in the 2010s.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp is an expression oriented language.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Unlike most other languages, no distinction is made between "expressions" and "statements"; all code and data are written as expressions.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] When an expression is *evaluated*, it produces a value (possibly multiple values), which can then be embedded into other expressions.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy's 1958 paper introduced two types of syntax: *Symbolic expressions* (S-expressions, sexps), which mirror the internal representation of code and data; and *Meta expressions* (M-expressions), which express functions of S-expressions.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] M-expressions never found favor, and almost all Lisps today use S-expressions to manipulate both code and data.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The use of parentheses is Lisp's most immediately obvious difference from other programming language families.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] As a result, students have long given Lisp nicknames such as *Lost In Stupid Parentheses*, or *Lots of Irritating Superfluous Parentheses*.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] However, the S-expression syntax is also responsible for much of Lisp's power: the syntax is simple and consistent, which facilitates manipulation by computer.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] However, the syntax of Lisp is not limited to traditional parentheses notation.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] It can be extended to include alternative notations.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] For example, XMLisp is a Common Lisp extension that employs the metaobject protocol to integrate S-expressions with the Extensible Markup Language (XML).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The reliance on expressions gives the language great flexibility.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Because Lisp functions are written as lists, they can be processed exactly like data.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This allows easy writing of programs which manipulate other programs (metaprogramming).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Many Lisp dialects exploit this feature using macro systems, which enables extension of the language almost without limit.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A Lisp list is written with its elements separated by whitespace, and surrounded by parentheses.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] For example, `(1 2 foo)` is a list whose elements are the three *atoms* `1`, `2`, and `foo`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] These values are implicitly typed: they are respectively two integers and a Lisp-specific data type called a "symbol", and do not have to be declared as such.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The empty list `()` is also represented as the special atom `nil`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This is the only entity in Lisp which is both an atom and a list.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Expressions are written as lists, using prefix notation.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The first element in the list is the name of a function, the name of a macro, a lambda expression or the name of a "special operator" (see below).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The remainder of the list are the arguments.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The "quote" before the `foo` in the preceding example is a "special operator" which returns its argument without evaluating it.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Any unquoted expressions are recursively evaluated before the enclosing expression is evaluated.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The third argument is a list; lists can be nested.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Arithmetic operators are treated similarly.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The equivalent under infix notation would be "`1 + 2 + 3 + 4`".
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp has no notion of operators as implemented in ALGOL-derived languages.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Arithmetic operators in Lisp are variadic functions (or *n-ary*), able to take any number of arguments.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] equivalent to `(setq x (+ x 1))`, returning the new value of `x`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] "Special operators" (sometimes called "special forms") provide Lisp's control structure.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] For example, the special operator `if` takes three arguments.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] If the first argument is non-nil, it evaluates to the second argument; otherwise, it evaluates to the third argument.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Of course, this would be more useful if a non-trivial expression had been substituted in place of `nil`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp also provides logical operators **and**, **or** and **not**.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The **and** and **or** operators do short-circuit evaluation and will return their first nil and non-nil argument respectively.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Another special operator, `lambda`, is used to bind variables to values which are then evaluated within an expression.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This operator is also used to create functions: the arguments to `lambda` are a list of arguments, and the expression or expressions to which the function evaluates (the returned value is the value of the last expression that is evaluated).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] evaluates to a function that, when applied, takes one argument, binds it to `arg` and returns the number one greater than that argument.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lambda expressions are treated no differently from named functions; they are invoked the same way.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Here, we're doing a function application: we execute the anonymous function by passing to it the value 5.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Named functions are created by storing a lambda expression in a symbol using the defun macro.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] `(defun f (a) b...)` defines a new function named `f` in the global environment.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] where `setf` is a macro used to set the value of the first argument `fdefinition 'f` to a new function object.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] `fdefinition` is a global function definition for the function named `f`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] `#'` is an abbreviation for `function` special operator, returning a function object.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] In the original **LISP** there were two fundamental data types: atoms and lists.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A list was a finite ordered sequence of elements, where each element is either an atom or a list, and an atom was a number or a symbol.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A symbol was essentially a unique named item, written as an alphanumeric string in source code, and used either as a variable name or as a data item in symbolic processing.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] For example, the list `(FOO (BAR 1) 2)` contains three elements: the symbol `FOO`, the list `(BAR 1)`, and the number 2.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The essential difference between atoms and lists was that atoms were immutable and unique.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Two atoms that appeared in different places in source code but were written in exactly the same way represented the same object, whereas each list was a separate object that could be altered independently of other lists and could be distinguished from other lists by comparison operators.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] As more data types were introduced in later Lisp dialects, and programming styles evolved, the concept of an atom lost importance.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Many dialects still retained the predicate *atom* for legacy compatibility, defining it true for any object which is not a cons.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A Lisp list is implemented as a singly linked list.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Each cell of this list is called a *cons* (in Scheme, a *pair*) and is composed of two pointers, called the *car* and *cdr*.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] These are respectively equivalent to the `data` and `next` fields discussed in the article *linked list*.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Of the many data structures that can be built out of cons cells, one of the most basic is called a *proper list*.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A proper list is either the special `nil` (empty list) symbol, or a cons in which the `car` points to a datum (which may be another cons structure, such as a list), and the `cdr` points to another proper list.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] If a given cons is taken to be the head of a linked list, then its car points to the first element of the list, and its cdr points to the rest of the list.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] For this reason, the `car` and `cdr` functions are also called `first` and `rest` when referring to conses which are part of a linked list (rather than, say, a tree).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Thus, a Lisp list is not an atomic object, as an instance of a container class in C++ or Java would be.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A list is nothing more than an aggregate of linked conses.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A variable that refers to a given list is simply a pointer to the first cons in the list.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Traversal of a list can be done by *cdring down* the list; that is, taking successive cdrs to visit each cons of the list; or by using any of several higher-order functions to map a function over a list.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Because conses and lists are so universal in Lisp systems, it is a common misconception that they are Lisp's only data structures.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] In fact, all but the most simplistic Lisps have other data structures, such as vectors (arrays), hash tables, structures, and so forth.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Parenthesized S-expressions represent linked list structures.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] There are several ways to represent the same list as an S-expression.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A cons can be written in *dotted-pair notation* as `(a . b)`, where `a` is the car and `b` the cdr.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A longer proper list might be written `(a .
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This is conventionally abbreviated as `(a b c d)` in *list notation*.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] An improper list may be written in a combination of the two – as `(a b c . d)` for the list of three conses whose last cdr is `d` (i.e., the list `(a .
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp provides many built-in procedures for accessing and controlling lists.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lists can be created directly with the `list` procedure, which takes any number of arguments, and returns the list of these arguments.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Because of the way that lists are constructed from cons pairs, the `cons` procedure can be used to add an element to the front of a list.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The `cons` procedure is asymmetric in how it handles list arguments, because of how lists are constructed.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The `append` procedure appends two (or more) lists to one another.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp lists, being simple linked lists, can share structure with one another.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] That is to say, two lists can have the same *tail*, or final sequence of conses.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] the lists `foo` and `bar` are `(a b c)` and `(x b c)` respectively.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] However, the tail `(b c)` is the same structure in both lists.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] It is not a copy; the cons cells pointing to `b` and `c` are in the same memory locations for both lists.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Sharing structure rather than copying can give a dramatic performance improvement.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] However, this technique can interact in undesired ways with functions that alter lists passed to them as arguments.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This changes `foo` to `(a b goose)`, but thereby also changes `bar` to `(x b goose)` – a possibly unexpected result.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This can be a source of bugs, and functions which alter their arguments are documented as *destructive* for this very reason.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Aficionados of functional programming avoid destructive functions.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] In the Scheme dialect, which favors the functional style, the names of destructive functions are marked with a cautionary exclamation point, or "bang"—such as `set-car!` (read *set car bang*), which replaces the car of a cons.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] In the Common Lisp dialect, destructive functions are commonplace; the equivalent of `set-car!` is named `rplaca` for "replace car".
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This function is rarely seen, however, as Common Lisp includes a special facility, `setf`, to make it easier to define and use destructive functions.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A frequent style in Common Lisp is to write code functionally (without destructive calls) when prototyping, then to add destructive calls as an optimization where it is safe to do so.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp evaluates expressions which are entered by the user.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Symbols and lists evaluate to some other (usually, simpler) expression – for instance, a symbol evaluates to the value of the variable it names; `(+ 2 3)` evaluates to `5`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] However, most other forms evaluate to themselves: if entering `5` into Lisp, it returns `5`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Any expression can also be marked to prevent it from being evaluated (as is necessary for symbols and lists).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This is the role of the `quote` special operator, or its abbreviation `'` (one quotation mark).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] For instance, usually if entering the symbol `foo`, it returns the value of the corresponding variable (or an error, if there is no such variable).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] To refer to the literal symbol, enter `(quote foo)` or, usually, `'foo`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Both Common Lisp and Scheme also support the *backquote* operator (termed *quasiquote* in Scheme), entered with the ` character (Backtick).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This is almost the same as the plain quote, except it allows expressions to be evaluated and their values interpolated into a quoted list with the comma `,` *unquote* and comma-at `,@` *splice* operators.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] If the variable `snue` has the value `(bar baz)` then `(foo ,snue) evaluates to `(foo (bar baz))`, while `(foo ,@snue) evaluates to `(foo bar baz)`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The backquote is most often used in defining macro expansions.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Self-evaluating forms and quoted forms are Lisp's equivalent of literals.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] It may be possible to modify the values of (mutable) literals in program code.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] For instance, if a function returns a quoted form, and the code that calls the function modifies the form, this may alter the behavior of the function on subsequent invocations.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Modifying a quoted form like this is generally considered bad style, and is defined by ANSI Common Lisp as erroneous (resulting in "undefined" behavior in compiled files, because the file-compiler can coalesce similar constants, put them in write-protected memory, etc.).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp's formalization of quotation has been noted by Douglas Hofstadter (in *Gödel, Escher, Bach*) and others as an example of the philosophical idea of self-reference.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The Lisp family splits over the use of dynamic or static (a.k.a. lexical) scope.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Clojure, Common Lisp and Scheme make use of static scoping by default, while newLISP, Picolisp and the embedded languages in Emacs and AutoCAD use dynamic scoping.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Since version 24.1, Emacs uses both dynamic and lexical scoping.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A fundamental distinction between Lisp and other languages is that in Lisp, the textual representation of a program is simply a human-readable description of the same internal data structures (linked lists, symbols, number, characters, etc.) as would be used by the underlying Lisp system.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp uses this to implement a very powerful macro system.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Like other macro languages such as the one defined by the C preprocessor (the macro preprocessor for the C, Objective-C and C++ programming languages), a macro returns code that can then be compiled.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] However, unlike C preprocessor macros, the macros are Lisp functions and so can exploit the full power of Lisp.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Further, because Lisp code has the same structure as lists, macros can be built with any of the list-processing functions in the language.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] In short, anything that Lisp can do to a data structure, Lisp macros can do to code.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] In contrast, in most other languages, the parser's output is purely internal to the language implementation and cannot be manipulated by the programmer.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This feature makes it easy to develop *efficient* languages within languages.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] For example, the Common Lisp Object System can be implemented cleanly as a language extension using macros.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This means that if an application needs a different inheritance mechanism, it can use a different object system.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This is in stark contrast to most other languages; for example, Java does not support multiple inheritance and there is no reasonable way to add it.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] In simplistic Lisp implementations, this list structure is directly interpreted to run the program; a function is literally a piece of list structure which is traversed by the interpreter in executing it.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] However, most substantial Lisp systems also include a compiler.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The compiler translates list structure into machine code or bytecode for execution.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This code can run as fast as code compiled in conventional languages such as C.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Macros expand before the compilation step, and thus offer some interesting options.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] If a program needs a precomputed table, then a macro might create the table at compile time, so the compiler need only output the table and need not call code to create the table at run time.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Some Lisp implementations even have a mechanism, `eval-when`, that allows code to be present during compile time (when a macro would need it), but not present in the emitted module.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp languages are often used with an interactive command line, which may be combined with an integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The user types in expressions at the command line, or directs the IDE to transmit them to the Lisp system.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp *reads* the entered expressions, *evaluates* them, and *prints* the result.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] For this reason, the Lisp command line is called a *read–eval–print loop* (REPL).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The basic operation of the REPL is as follows.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This is a simplistic description which omits many elements of a real Lisp, such as quoting and macros.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The `read` function accepts textual S-expressions as input, and parses them into an internal data structure.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] For instance, if you type the text `(+ 1 2)` at the prompt, `read` translates this into a linked list with three elements: the symbol `+`, the number 1, and the number 2.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] It so happens that this list is also a valid piece of Lisp code; that is, it can be evaluated.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This is because the car of the list names a function—the addition operation.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A `foo` will be read as a single symbol.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] `123` will be read as the number one hundred and twenty-three.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The `eval` function evaluates the data, returning zero or more other Lisp data as a result.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Evaluation does not have to mean interpretation; some Lisp systems compile every expression to native machine code.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] It is simple, however, to describe evaluation as interpretation: To evaluate a list whose car names a function, `eval` first evaluates each of the arguments given in its cdr, then applies the function to the arguments.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] In this case, the function is addition, and applying it to the argument list `(1 2)` yields the answer `3`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The symbol `foo` evaluates to the value of the symbol foo.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Data like the string "123" evaluates to the same string.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The list `(quote (1 2 3))` evaluates to the list (1 2 3).
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] It is the job of the `print` function to represent output to the user.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] For a simple result such as `3` this is trivial.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] An expression which evaluated to a piece of list structure would require that `print` traverse the list and print it out as an S-expression.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] To implement a Lisp REPL, it is necessary only to implement these three functions and an infinite-loop function.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] (Naturally, the implementation of `eval` will be complex, since it must also implement all special operators like `if` or `lambda`.) This done, a basic REPL is one line of code: `(loop (print (eval (read))))`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The Lisp REPL typically also provides input editing, an input history, error handling and an interface to the debugger.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] In Common Lisp, arguments are evaluated in applicative order ('leftmost innermost'), while in Scheme order of arguments is undefined, leaving room for optimization by a compiler.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp originally had very few control structures, but many more were added during the language's evolution.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Programmers in the Scheme dialect often express loops using tail recursion.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Scheme's commonality in academic computer science has led some students to believe that tail recursion is the only, or the most common, way to write iterations in Lisp, but this is incorrect.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] All oft-seen Lisp dialects have imperative-style iteration constructs, from Scheme's `do` loop to Common Lisp's complex `loop` expressions.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] By contrast, ANSI Common Lisp does not require the optimization commonly termed a tail call elimination.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Some Lisp control structures are *special operators*, equivalent to other languages' syntactic keywords.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Expressions using these operators have the same surface appearance as function calls, but differ in that the arguments are not necessarily evaluated—or, in the case of an iteration expression, may be evaluated more than once.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] In contrast to most other major programming languages, Lisp allows implementing control structures using the language.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Several control structures are implemented as Lisp macros, and can even be macro-expanded by the programmer who wants to know how they work.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Both Common Lisp and Scheme have operators for non-local control flow.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The differences in these operators are some of the deepest differences between the two dialects.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Scheme supports *re-entrant continuations* using the `call/cc` procedure, which allows a program to save (and later restore) a particular place in execution.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp does not support re-entrant continuations, but does support several ways of handling escape continuations.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Often, the same algorithm can be expressed in Lisp in either an imperative or a functional style.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] As noted above, Scheme tends to favor the functional style, using tail recursion and continuations to express control flow.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] However, imperative style is still quite possible.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] The style preferred by many Common Lisp programmers may seem more familiar to programmers used to structured languages such as C, while that preferred by Schemers more closely resembles pure-functional languages such as Haskell.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Because of Lisp's early heritage in list processing, it has a wide array of higher-order functions relating to iteration over sequences.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] In many cases where an explicit loop would be needed in other languages (like a `for` loop in C) in Lisp the same task can be accomplished with a higher-order function.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] A good example is a function which in Scheme is called `map` and in Common Lisp is called `mapcar`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] This applies the `+` function to each corresponding pair of list elements, yielding the result `(11 22 33 44 55)`.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Lisp syntax lends itself naturally to recursion.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Mathematical problems such as the enumeration of recursively defined sets are simple to express in this notation.
[src:elisp-deep/lisp-programming-language] Genera, renamed Open Genera, by Symbolics; Medley, written in Interlisp, originally a family of graphical operating systems that ran on Xerox's later Star workstations; Mezzano; Interim; ChrysaLisp, by developers of Tao Systems' TAOS; and also the Guix System for GNU/Linux.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman launched the GNU Project in September 1983 to write a Unix-like computer operating system composed entirely of free software.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] With that he also launched the free software movement.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He has been GNU Project's lead architect and organizer, and developed a number of pieces of widely used GNU software including among others, the GNU C Compiler (GCC) version 1.0 (that later was expanded and renamed GNU Compiler Collection), GNU Debugger, and GNU Emacs text editor.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman pioneered the concept of copyleft, which uses the principles of copyright law to preserve the right to use, modify, and distribute free software.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He is the main author of free software licenses which describe those terms, most notably the GNU General Public License (GPL), the most widely used free software license.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In 1989, he co-founded the League for Programming Freedom.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In September 2019, Stallman resigned as president of the FSF and left his visiting scientist role at MIT after making controversial comments about the Jeffrey Epstein sex trafficking scandal.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman remained head of the GNU Project, and in 2021 returned to the FSF board of directors and others.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman was born March 16, 1953 in New York City, to a family of Jewish heritage.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He had a troublesome relationship with his parents and did not feel he had a proper home.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He was interested in computers at a young age; when he was a pre-teen at a summer camp, he read manuals for the IBM 7094.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] From 1967 to 1969, Stallman attended a Columbia University Saturday program for high school students.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He was also a volunteer laboratory assistant in the biology department at Rockefeller University.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Although he was interested in mathematics and physics, his supervising professor at Rockefeller thought he showed promise as a biologist.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] His first experience with actual computers was at the IBM New York Scientific Center when he was in high school.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He was hired for the summer in 1970 after his senior year of high school, to write a numerical analysis program in Fortran.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He completed the task after a couple of weeks ("I swore that I would never use FORTRAN again because I despised it as a language compared with other languages") and spent the rest of the summer writing a text editor in APL and a preprocessor for the PL/I programming language on the IBM System/360.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] As a first-year student at Harvard University in fall 1970, Stallman was known for his strong performance in Math 55.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In 1971, near the end of his first year at Harvard, he became a programmer at the MIT Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, and became a regular in the hacker community, where he was usually known by his initials, *RMS*, which he used in his computer accounts.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman received a bachelor's degree in physics (*magna cum laude*) from Harvard in 1974.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He considered staying on at Harvard, but instead decided to enroll as a graduate student at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He pursued a doctorate in physics for one year, but left the program to focus on his programming at the MIT AI Laboratory.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] While working (starting in 1975) as a research assistant at MIT under Gerry Sussman, Stallman published a paper (with Sussman) in 1977 on an AI truth maintenance system, called *dependency-directed backtracking*.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] The paper was an early work on the problem of intelligent backtracking in constraint satisfaction problems.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] As of 2009, the technique Stallman and Sussman introduced was still the most general and powerful form of intelligent backtracking.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] The technique of constraint recording, wherein partial results of a search are recorded for later reuse, was also introduced in this paper.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He became an ardent critic of restricted computer access in the lab, which at that time was funded primarily by the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA).
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Around 20 percent of the users followed his advice at the time, although passwords ultimately prevailed.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman boasted of the success of his campaign for many years afterward.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In the late 1970s and early 1980s, the hacker culture which Stallman thrived on began to fragment.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] To prevent software from being used on their competitors' computers, most manufacturers stopped distributing source code and began using copyright and restrictive software licenses to limit or prohibit copying and redistribution.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Such proprietary software had existed before, and it became apparent that it would become the norm.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] This shift in the legal characteristics of software was a consequence triggered by the US Copyright Act of 1976.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] When Brian Reid in 1979 placed time bombs in the Scribe markup language and word processing system to restrict unlicensed access to the software, Stallman proclaimed it "a crime against humanity".
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] During an interview in 2008, he clarified that it is blocking the user's freedom that he believes is a crime, not the issue of charging for software.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman's texinfo is a GPL replacement, loosely based on Scribe; the original version was finished in 1986.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In 1980, Stallman and some other hackers at the AI Lab were refused access to the source code for the software of a newly installed laser printer, the Xerox 9700.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman had modified the software for the Lab's previous laser printer (the XGP, Xerographic Printer), so it electronically messaged a user when the person's job was printed, and would message all logged-in users waiting for print jobs if the printer was jammed.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Not being able to add these features to the new printer was a major inconvenience, as the printer was on a different floor from most of the users.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] This experience convinced Stallman of people's need to be able to freely modify the software they use.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Richard Greenblatt, a fellow AI Lab hacker, founded Lisp Machines, Inc.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] (LMI) to market Lisp machines, which he and Tom Knight designed at the lab.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Greenblatt rejected outside investment, believing that the proceeds from the construction and sale of a few machines could be profitably reinvested in the growth of the company.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In contrast, the other hackers felt that the venture capital-funded approach was better.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] As no agreement could be reached, hackers from the latter camp founded Symbolics, with the aid of Russ Noftsker, an AI Lab administrator.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Symbolics recruited most of the remaining hackers including notable hacker Bill Gosper, who then left the AI Lab.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Symbolics also forced Greenblatt to resign by citing MIT policies.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] While both companies delivered proprietary software, Stallman believed that LMI, unlike Symbolics, had tried to avoid hurting the lab's community.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] For two years, from 1982 to the end of 1983, Stallman worked by himself to clone the output of the Symbolics programmers, to prevent them from gaining a monopoly on the lab's computers.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman argues that software users should have the freedom to share with their neighbors and be able to study and make changes to the software that they use.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He maintains that attempts by proprietary software vendors to prohibit these acts are antisocial and unethical.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] The phrase "software wants to be free" is often incorrectly attributed to him, and Stallman argues that this is a misstatement of his philosophy.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He argues that freedom is vital for the sake of users and society as a moral *value*, and not merely for pragmatic reasons such as possibly developing technically superior software.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Raymond, one of the creators of the open-source movement, argues that moral arguments, rather than pragmatic ones, alienate potential allies and hurt the end goal of removing code secrecy.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In February 1984, Stallman quit his job at MIT to work full-time on the GNU project, which he had announced in September 1983.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Since then, he had remained affiliated with MIT as an unpaid "visiting scientist" in the Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Until "around 1998", he maintained an office at the Institute that doubled as his legal residence.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman announced the plan for the GNU operating system in September 1983 on several ARPANET mailing lists and USENET.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He started the project on his own and describes: "As an operating system developer, I had the right skills for this job.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] So even though I could not take success for granted, I realized that I was elected to do the job.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In 1985, Stallman published the GNU Manifesto, which outlined his motivation for creating a free operating system called GNU, which would be compatible with Unix.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] The name GNU is a recursive acronym for "GNU's Not Unix".
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Soon after, he started a nonprofit corporation called the Free Software Foundation to employ free software programmers and provide a legal infrastructure for the free software movement.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman was the nonsalaried president of the FSF, which is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization founded in Massachusetts.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman popularized the concept of *copyleft*, a legal mechanism to protect the modification and redistribution rights for free software.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] It was first implemented in the GNU Emacs General Public License, and in 1989 the first program-independent GNU General Public License (GPL) was released.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] By then, much of the GNU system had been completed.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman was responsible for contributing many necessary tools, including a text editor (GNU Emacs), compiler (GCC), debugger (GNU Debugger), and a build automator (GNU make).
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In 1990, members of the GNU project began using Carnegie Mellon's Mach microkernel in a project called GNU Hurd, which has yet to achieve the maturity level required for full POSIX compliance.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In 1991, Linus Torvalds, a Finnish student studying at the University of Helsinki, used the GNU's development tools to produce the free monolithic Linux kernel.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] The existing programs from the GNU project were readily ported to run on the resultant platform.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Most sources use the name *Linux* to refer to the general-purpose operating system thus formed, while Stallman and the FSF call it *GNU/Linux*.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] This has been a longstanding naming controversy in the free software community.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman argues that not using GNU in the name of the operating system unfairly disparages the value of the GNU project and harms the sustainability of the free software movement by breaking the link between the software and the free software philosophy of the GNU project.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman's influences on hacker culture include the name POSIX and the Emacs editor.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] On Unix systems, GNU Emacs's popularity rivaled that of another editor vi, spawning an editor war.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman's take on this was to canonize himself as St.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] IGNUcius of the Church of Emacs and acknowledge that "vi vi vi is the editor of the beast", while "using a free version of vi is not a sin; it is a penance".
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In 1992, developers at Lucid Inc. doing their own work on Emacs clashed with Stallman and ultimately forked the software into what would become XEmacs.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In 2018, Stallman instituted "Kind Communication Guidelines" for the GNU project to help its mailing list discussions remain constructive while avoiding explicitly promoting diversity.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In October 2019, a public statement signed by 33 maintainers of the GNU project asserted that Stallman's behaviour had "undermined a core value of the GNU project: the empowerment of all computer users" and called for "GNU maintainers to collectively decide about the organization of the project".
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] The statement was published soon after Stallman resigned as president of the FSF and left his "visiting scientist" role at MIT in September 2019.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In spite of that, Stallman remained head of the GNU project.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman has written many essays on software freedom, and has been an outspoken political campaigner for the free software movement since the early 1990s.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] The speeches he has regularly given are titled *The GNU Project and the Free Software Movement*, *The Dangers of Software Patents*, and *Copyright and Community in the Age of Computer Networks*.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In 2006 and 2007, during the eighteen month public consultation for the drafting of version 3 of the GNU General Public License, he added a fourth topic explaining the proposed changes.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman's staunch advocacy for free software inspired the creation of the Virtual Richard M.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman (vrms), software that analyzes the packages currently installed on a Debian system, and reports those that are from the non-free tree.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman disagrees with parts of Debian's definition of free software.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In 1999, Stallman called for development of a free online encyclopedia through the means of inviting the public to contribute articles.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] The resulting GNUPedia was eventually retired in favour of the emerging Wikipedia, which had similar aims and was enjoying greater success.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman was on the Advisory Council of Latin American television station teleSUR from its launch but resigned in February 2011, criticizing pro-Gaddafi propaganda during the Arab Spring.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In August 2006, at his meetings with the government of the Indian State of Kerala, he persuaded officials to discard proprietary software, such as Microsoft's, at state-run schools.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] This has resulted in a landmark decision to switch all school computers in 12,500 high schools from Windows to a free software operating system.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] After personal meetings, Stallman obtained positive statements about the free software movement from the then-president of India, A.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Abdul Kalam, French 2007 presidential candidate Ségolène Royal, and the president of Ecuador Rafael Correa.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman has participated in protests about software patents, digital rights management, and proprietary software.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Protesting against proprietary software in April 2006, Stallman held a "Don't buy from ATI, enemy of your freedom" placard at an invited talk given by an ATI compiler architect in the building where Stallman worked, resulting in the police being called.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] AMD has since acquired ATI and has taken steps to make their hardware documentation available for use by the free software community.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman has characterized Steve Jobs as having a "malign influence" on computing because of Jobs' leadership in guiding Apple to produce closed platforms.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] According to Stallman, while Jobs was at NeXT, Jobs asked Stallman if he could distribute a modified GCC in two parts, one part under GPL and the other part, an Objective-C preprocessor under a proprietary license.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman initially thought this would be legal, but since he also thought it would be "very undesirable for free software", he asked a lawyer for advice.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] The response he got was that judges would consider such schemes to be "subterfuges" and would be very harsh toward them, and a judge would ask whether it was "really" one program, rather than how the parts were labeled.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Therefore, Stallman sent a message back to Jobs which said they believed Jobs' plan was not allowed by the GPL, which resulted in NeXT releasing the Objective-C front end under GPL.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] For a period of time, Stallman used a notebook from the One Laptop per Child program.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman's computer is a refurbished ThinkPad X200 with Libreboot (a free BIOS replacement), and Trisquel.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Before the ThinkPad X200, Stallman used a ThinkPad T400s with Libreboot and Trisquel.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] And before the T400s, Stallman used a ThinkPad X60, and even further back in time, a Lemote Yeeloong netbook (using the same company's Loongson processor) which he chose because, like the X200, X60 and the T400s, it could run with free software at the BIOS level, stating "freedom is my priority.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] I've campaigned for freedom since 1983, and I am not going to surrender that freedom for the sake of a more convenient computer." Stallman's Lemote was stolen from him in 2012 while he was in Argentina.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Before Trisquel, Stallman has used the gNewSense operating system.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman has regularly given a talk entitled "Copyright vs.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Community" where he reviews the state of digital rights management (DRM) and names many of the products and corporations which he boycotts.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] His approach to DRM is best summed up by the FSF Defective by Design campaign.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In the talks, he makes proposals for a "reduced copyright" and suggests a 10-year limit on copyright.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He indicates that no form of non-commercial sharing of copies should be considered a copyright violation.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He has advocated for civil disobedience in a comment on Ley Sinde.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He has reportedly refused to autograph anything bearing a '©' symbol, in line with his views.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman has helped and supported the International Music Score Library Project get back online, after it had been taken down on October 19, 2007, following a cease and desist letter from Universal Edition.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman mentions the dangers some e-books bring compared to paper books, with the example of the Amazon Kindle e-reader that prevents the copying of e-books and allows Amazon to order automatic deletion of a book.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He says that such e-books present a big step backward with respect to paper books by being less easy to use, copy, lend to others or sell, also mentioning that Amazon e-books cannot be bought anonymously.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] His short story "The Right to Read" provides a picture of a dystopian future if the right to share books is impeded.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He objects to many of the terms within typical end-user license agreements that accompany e-books.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He discourages the use of several storage technologies such as DVD or Blu-ray video discs because the content of such media is encrypted.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He considers manufacturers' use of encryption on non-secret data (to force the user to view certain promotional material) as a conspiracy.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman recognized the Sony BMG copy protection rootkit scandal to be a criminal act by Sony and supports a general boycott of Sony for its legal actions against George Hotz.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman has suggested that the United States government may encourage the use of software as a service because this would allow them to access users' data without needing a search warrant.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He denies being an anarchist despite his wariness of some legislation and the fact that he has "advocated strongly for user privacy and his own view of software freedom".
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman places great importance on the words and labels people use to talk about the world, including the relationship between software and freedom.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He asks people to say *free software* and *GNU/Linux*, and to avoid the terms *intellectual property* and *piracy* (in relation to copying not approved by the publisher).
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] One of his criteria for giving an interview to a journalist is that the journalist agrees to use his terminology throughout the article.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman argues that the term *intellectual property* is designed to confuse people, and is used to prevent intelligent discussion on the specifics of copyright, patent, trademark, and other areas of law by lumping together things that are more dissimilar than similar.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] His requests that people use certain terms, and his ongoing efforts to convince people of the importance of terminology, are a source of regular misunderstanding and friction with parts of the free software and open-source communities.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] After initially accepting the concept, Stallman rejects a common alternative term, *open-source software*, because it does not call to mind what Stallman sees as the value of the software: freedom.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He wrote, "Free software is a political movement; open source is a development model." Thus, he believes that the use of the term will not inform people of the freedom issues, and will not lead to people valuing and defending their freedom.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Two alternatives which Stallman does accept are *software libre* and *unfettered software*, but *free software* is the term he asks people to use in English.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] For similar reasons, he argues for the term *proprietary software* or *non-free software* rather than *closed-source software*, when referring to software that is not free software.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman asks that the term *GNU/Linux*, which he pronounces /ɡnuː slæʃ ˈlɪnəks/ *GNOO SLASH LIN-əks*, be used to refer to the operating system created by combining the GNU system and the kernel Linux.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman refers to this operating system as "a variant of GNU, and the GNU Project is its principal developer".
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He claims that the connection between the GNU project's philosophy and its software is broken when people refer to the combination as merely Linux.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] The creator of Linux, Linus Torvalds, has publicly said that he objects to modification of the name and that the rename "is their [the FSF] confusion not ours".
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman professes admiration for Julian Assange and Edward Snowden.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He has spoken against government and corporate surveillance on many occasions.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He refers to mobile phones as "portable surveillance and tracking devices", refusing to own a cell phone due to the lack of phones running entirely on free software.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He also avoids using a key card to enter his office building since key card systems track each location and time that someone enters the building using a card.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He usually does not browse the web directly from his personal computer.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Instead, he uses GNU Womb's grab-url-from-mail utility, an email-based proxy which downloads the webpage content and then emails it to the user.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In a 2016 interview, he said that he accesses all websites via Tor, except for Wikipedia (which generally disallows editing from Tor).
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In September 2019, it was learned that Jeffrey Epstein had made donations to MIT, and in the wake of this, MIT Media Lab director Joi Ito resigned.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] An internal MIT CSAIL listserv mailing list thread was started to protest the coverup of MIT's connections to Epstein.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In the thread, discussion had turned to deceased MIT professor Marvin Minsky, who was named by Virginia Giuffre as one of the people that Maxwell had directed her to go have sex with.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Giuffre, a minor at the time, had been caught in Epstein's underage sex trafficking ring.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman was unambiguous in his condemnation of Epstein, stating "We know that Giuffre was being coerced into sex–by Epstein.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He also argued that the moral harm to the victim does not depend on technical legal definitions, stating "It is morally absurd to define 'rape' in a way that depends on minor details such as which country it was in or whether the victim was 18 years old or 17".
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman's comments, along with a compilation of accusations against him, were published via Medium by Selam Gano, who called for him to be removed from MIT.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] *Vice* published a copy of the email chain on September 13, 2019.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Tied to his comments regarding Minsky, several called for Stallman's resignation.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Separately, older writings by Stallman from 2013 and earlier on underage sex and child pornography laws resurfaced during the controversy.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] On September 14, 2019, Stallman acknowledged that since the time of those writings, he had learned that there were problems with underage sex, writing on his blog: "Through personal conversations in recent years, I've learned to understand how sex with a child can harm per psychologically.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] On September 16, 2019, Stallman announced his resignation from both MIT and FSF, "due to pressure on MIT and me over a series of misunderstandings and mischaracterizations".
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In a post on his website, Stallman asserted that his posts to the email lists were not to defend Epstein, stating "Nothing could be further from the truth.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] I've called him a 'serial rapist', and said he deserved to be imprisoned.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] But many people now believe I defended him—and other inaccurate claims—and feel a real hurt because of what they believe I said.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In March 2021, at LibrePlanet2021, Stallman announced his return to the FSF board of directors.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] An open letter asking for the FSF to retain Stallman was published, arguing that his statements had been mischaracterized, misunderstood, and needed to be interpreted in context.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] The FSF board on April 12 made a statement re-affirming its decision to bring back Stallman.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] After that, Stallman issued a statement apologizing and explaining his poor social skills.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Shortly thereafter, a separate open letter was also published on GitHub asking for the removal of Stallman along with the entire FSF board of directors, supported by prominent open-source organizations including GNOME and Mozilla, and including a list of accusations against Stallman.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Multiple organizations criticized, defunded, and/or cut ties with the FSF including Red Hat, the Free Software Foundation Europe, the Software Freedom Conservancy, SUSE, the OSI, the Document Foundation, the EFF, and the Tor Project.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Debian declined to issue a statement after a community vote on the matter.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] However, the FSF noted that this had relatively little financial impact, as direct financial support from corporations accounted for less than 3% of its revenue in the most recent fiscal year.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman lives in Boston and moved there after living in Cambridge, Massachusetts for many years.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He speaks English, French, Spanish and some Indonesian.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He has said that he is "an atheist of Jewish ancestry" and often wears a button that reads "Impeach God".
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman denies having autism, but suffers from the Asperger syndrome.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] Stallman has written a collection of filk music and parody songs.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] In September 2023, while giving his keynote presentation at the GNU 40th anniversary event, Stallman revealed he had been diagnosed with follicular lymphoma, a form of cancer, and said that his prognosis was good and he hopes to be around for years to come.
[src:elisp-deep/richard-stallman] He later stated he was in remission and he was getting treatment.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] In computer programming, an **S-expression** (or **symbolic expression**, abbreviated as **sexpr** or **sexp**) is an expression in a like-named notation for nested list (tree-structured) data.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] S-expressions were invented for, and popularized by, the programming language Lisp, which uses them for source code as well as data.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] *y*) where *x* and *y* are S-expressions.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] This definition reflects LISP's representation of a list as a series of "cells", each one an ordered pair.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] In plain lists, *y* points to the next cell (if any), thus forming a list.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] The recursive clause of the definition means that both this representation and the S-expression notation can represent any binary tree.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] `NIL` is the special end-of-list object (alternatively written `()`, which is the only representation in Scheme).
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] In the Lisp family of programming languages, S-expressions are used to represent both source code and data.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] Other uses of S-expressions are in Lisp-derived languages such as DSSSL, and as mark-up in communication protocols like IMAP and John McCarthy's CBCL.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] It is also used as text representation of WebAssembly.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] The details of the syntax and supported data types vary in the different languages, but the most common feature among these languages is the use of S-expressions and prefix notation.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] There are many variants of the S-expression format, supporting a variety of different syntaxes for different datatypes.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] The character `#` is often used to prefix extensions to the syntax, e.g.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] `#x10` for hexadecimal integers, or `#\C` for characters.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] When representing source code in Lisp, the first element of an S-expression is commonly an operator or function name and any remaining elements are treated as arguments.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] This is called "prefix notation" or "Polish notation".
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] As an example, the Boolean expression written `4 == (2 + 2)` in C, is represented as `(= 4 (+ 2 2))` in Lisp's s-expr-based prefix notation.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] As noted above, the precise definition of "atom" varies across LISP-like languages.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] A quoted string can typically contain anything but a quote, while an unquoted identifier atom can typically contain anything but quotes, whitespace characters, parentheses, brackets, braces, backslashes, and semicolons.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] In either case, a prohibited character can typically be included by escaping it with a preceding backslash.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] The recursive case of the definition of S-expressions is traditionally implemented using cons cells.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] S-expressions were originally intended only for data to be manipulated by M-expressions, but the first implementation of Lisp was an interpreter of S-expression encodings of M-expressions, and Lisp programmers soon became accustomed to using S-expressions for both code and data.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] This means that Lisp is homoiconic; that is, the primary representation of programs is also a data structure in a primitive type of the language itself.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] Nested lists can be written as S-expressions: `((milk juice) (honey marmalade))` is a two-element S-expression whose elements are also two-element S-expressions.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] The whitespace-separated notation used in Lisp (and this article) is typical.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] Line breaks (newline characters) usually qualify as separators.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] Program code can be written in S-expressions, usually using prefix notation.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] S-expressions can be read in Lisp using the function READ.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] READ reads the textual representation of an S-expression and returns Lisp data.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] The function PRINT can be used to output an S-expression.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] The output then can be read with the function READ, when all printed data objects have a readable representation.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] Lisp has readable representations for numbers, strings, symbols, lists and many other data types.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] Program code can be formatted as pretty printed S-expressions using the function PPRINT (note: with two Ps, short for *pretty*-print).
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] Lisp programs are valid S-expressions, but not all S-expressions are valid Lisp programs.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] `(1.0 + 3.1)` is a valid S-expression, but not a valid Lisp program, since Lisp uses prefix notation and a floating point number (here 1.0) is not valid as an operation (the first element of the expression).
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] An S-expression preceded by a single quotation mark, as in `'x`, is syntactic sugar for a quoted S-expression, in this case `(quote x)`.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] S-expressions are also used for WebAssembly text format.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] S-expressions are often compared to XML: one key difference is that S-expressions have just one form of containment, the dotted pair, while XML tags can contain simple attributes, other tags, or CDATA, each using different syntax.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] Another is that S-expressions do not define a reference mechanism, whereas XML provides a notion of unique identifiers and references to them.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] For simple use cases, S-expressions are simpler than XML, but for more advanced use cases, XML has a query language called XPath which many tools and third party libraries use to simplify the handling of XML data.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] Standards for some Lisp-derived programming languages include a specification for their S-expression syntax.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] These include Common Lisp (ANSI standard document ANSI INCITS 226-1994 (R2004)), Scheme (R5RS and R6RS), and ISLISP.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] In May 1997, Ron Rivest submitted an Internet Draft to be considered for publication as an RFC.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] The draft defined a syntax based on Lisp S-expressions but intended for general-purpose data storage and exchange (similar to XML) rather than specifically for programming.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] It was never approved as an RFC, but it has since been cited and used by other RFCs (e.g.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] RFC 2693) and several other publications.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] It was originally intended for use in SPKI.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] Rivest's format defines an S-expression as being either an octet-string (a series of bytes) or a finite list of other S-expressions.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] It describes three interchange formats for expressing this structure.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] One is the "advanced transport", which is very flexible in terms of formatting, and is syntactically similar to Lisp-style expressions, but they are not identical.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] The advanced transport, for example, allows octet-strings to be represented verbatim (the string's length followed by a colon and the entire raw string), a quoted form allowing escape characters, hexadecimal, Base64, or placed directly as a "token" if it meets certain conditions.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] Rivest's draft defines a canonical representation "for digital signature purposes".
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] It is intended to be compact, easier to parse, and unique for any abstract S-expression.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] It only allows verbatim strings, and prohibits whitespace as formatting outside strings.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] This format has not been widely adapted for use outside of SPKI (some of the users being GnuPG, libgcrypt, Nettle, and GNU lsh).
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] Rivest's S-expressions web page provides C source code for a parser and generator (available under the MIT license), which could be adapted and embedded into other programs.
[src:elisp-deep/s-expression] In addition, there are no restrictions on independently implementing the format.
